by Josh Iden¶

Introduction¶

  • This analysis focuses on a Ford GoBike data set provided by Udacity, which includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay Area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataframe consists of 183,412 rows and 16 columns

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The dataset includes information about bike rentals, including time of rental, duration of rental, as well as information about the stations - start/end stations, station name/location, and information about the individual users, including birth year and gender.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features which I think are most interesting are the dates, the latitude/longitude of the stations, and the duration of the trips. I'm interested in which days are most popular, which stations are most popular, and the trends around distribution of distance and duration of the trips. I am also interested in data about riders, including which riders tend to be most active and when, and rider trends regarding duration and speed. In order to attain this information, new columns will need to be created.

What is the Distribution of Distance per Rides?¶

Next I'd like to take a look at the distribution of distances across all rides. To do this, I'll create a column in the dataframe which calculates the distance from the starting latitude/longitude to the ending latitude longitude using the Haversein formula.

In [35]:
# haversine function to calculate distance in km between two points
# credit https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29545704/fast-haversine-approximation-python-pandas/29546836#29546836
def haversine_np(lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2):
    """
    Calculate the great circle distance between two points
    on the earth (specified in decimal degrees)

    All args must be of equal length.    

    """
    lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2 = map(np.radians, [lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2])

    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    dlat = lat2 - lat1

    a = np.sin(dlat/2.0)**2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin(dlon/2.0)**2

    c = 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))
    km = 6367 * c
    return km
In [36]:
# loop through the dataframe creating the distance_km column
for row in df:
    start_lat = df.start_station_latitude
    end_lat = df.end_station_latitude
    start_lon = df.start_station_longitude
    end_lon = df.end_station_longitude
    df['distance_km'] = haversine_np(start_lon, start_lat, end_lon, end_lat)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

From the univariate exploration I observe the following:

  • The average rider age is 37; half of all riders are between 21-35
  • 75% of all rides are 2.2 km in distance or less
  • 75% of all rides are 13 minutes in duration or less
  • 71% of all riders are male
  • 89% of all rides are by Subscribers
  • Weekdays are more popular for riders than weekends

In order to obtain these insights, I performed the following transformations:

  • Created a day of week column
  • Created a categorical weekday/weekend column
  • Created an age column subtracting year of birth from the current year
  • Created a distance column based on the starting and ending geocoordinates
  • Created a minutes series based on distance given in seconds in order to gain a clearer insight of ride duration

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There were a number of outliers and null values which were addressed. These were:

  • Start Time/End Time columns were in string format, which I converted to datetime objects
  • Member Gender columns contained NA values, which I replaced with Not Given
  • Some Start Station and End Station columns contained null values, which corresponded to inconsistent values in the latitude and longitude columns rounded to fewer decimals. As this did not affect the analysis and the observations contained other useful data, these were left as is
  • Member Birth Year contained outliers which I determined to be data entry errors (ages over 100), and were replaced with null values

def pct_diff(a, b):
    '''calculates the percentage difference between two variables'''
    diff = round(((a - b) / ((a + b) / 2)) * 100, 2)
    return diff
In [65]:

Conclusions¶

• The dataset contains information about Ford GoBikes in the San Francisco market for Feb 2019.
• Weekdays are nearly twice as popular than weekends for ridership, suggesting that riders in this market are utilizing the GoBikes for commuting to work or school or other weekday commitments.
• The median age of riders is 35, suggesting most riders are commuting for work
• The average ride is 1.69 km in distance and 9 mins in duration, 75% of rides are 2.2km or less, and 13 mins or less.
• The bike service is far more popular amongst males than females, as males account for 71% of all rides
• 89% of all rides are by subscribers (regular riders). Customers (casual riders) account for only 11% of all rides
• Subscribers ride twice as fast as Customers
• Riders ride about 12% faster during the week than on weekends
